pullRequest.body:
This syntax linter emits a warning on declarations whose name ends with a `'` and that have no doc-string.

By default, the linter is
* `on` on `mathlib` and
* `off` on projects depending on mathlib.

The file `scripts/no_lints_prime_decls.txt` contains the current exceptions.

The exceptions need to be managed manually by design: the expectation is that, once the linter starts, the nolints file should only decrease and never increase.  In particular, after the linter flags a declaration, simply adding manually an exception is *not enough* for CI to be successful.  There needs to be a change in the file with the exception (or upstream from it), since otherwise `lake` will replay the `olean`s and keep emitting the initial warning.  The expectation is that the change will be the addition of a doc-string.

---

```bash
#!/bin/bash

# a script to update the `docPrime`-linter exceptions
(
  fil=scripts/no_lints_prime_decls.txt
  {
    lake build --no-build |
      awk -F'`' '/warning/ {print $2}'
    cat "${fil}"
  } |
    sort -u > "${fil}.tmp"
  mv "${fil}.tmp" "${fil}"
)
```

ðŸš€ Pull request has been placed on the maintainer queue by grunweg.
I propose tracking the length of the exceptions file in the technical debt script. Do you prefer me pushing a commit to this PR, or a separate PR?

Michael, thank you very much for comments and commits!

As usual, I probably prefer a separate PR for the tech-debts update.  This linter is so annoying when it comes to adding exceptions that I would not want to risk it having to go through any more CI cycles than are strictly necessary!

Is this already ready to be active in Mathlib? We still have a bunch of (unofficial) naming conventions with primes `foo_le'` is often a reversed version of `foo_le` in some way, and I'm not sure we already want to deploy this before we "fix" these naming conventions? It's might 

I guess the vote in https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/287929-mathlib4/topic/theorem.20names.20with.20primes.3F was pretty overwhelming.

Actually, that number of lemmas is probably tiny.
So we require all primed projection names to have doc-strings referring to the unprimed ones (which are usually defeq)?

Floris, yes, requiring primed projection names to have a doc-string.  It seems like a good policy to require a doc-string for a declaration that is already trying to tell you that it is analogous to another one and explaining the difference seems like a very positive outcome.

I'm not sure how I feel about the specific case of projections, but it isn't too bad to add a docstring anyway.

Thanks for writing this linter!
I just took a look, and have only minor comments. From my side, this looks good to go - feel free to maintainer merge on my behalf once you have addressed these nits.
(There may also be a few new exceptions to add.)

```suggestion
        Declarations whose name contains a `'` are expected to contain an explanation for the \
        presence of a `'` in their doc-string. This may consist of discussion of the difference \
        relative to the unprimed version, or an explanation as to why no better naming scheme \
        is possible."
```
Or something like it.

```suggestion
      m!"`{declId}` is missing a doc-string, please add one.\n\
```

```suggestion
 unless [``Lean.Parser.Command.declaration, `lemma].contains stx.getKind do return

Can you extend this docstring slightly, using e.g.
- something like this: "They should have a doc-string, explaining (among others) why the primed name was chosen
(and how this declaration differs from its unprimed version, if applicable)."
- or part of your error message below (which I only saw later, and might be much nicer than this wording!)
What do you think about "contains a list of temporary exceptions to this linter, which is intended to become empty over time"?

I just pushed a commit clarifying/commenting this slightly.

That said, this kind of syntax parsing feels quite brittle. I wonder if there's a better way to do this... but perhaps this is fine as-is.
To clarify: I won't block landing the linter on that. To me, this is a question worth thinking about, but not worth stalling this PR on.

An alternative could be to retrieve the declaration name and ask for `hasDocstring` or similar.  In any case, I would probably worry about this if we get reports of the linter not behaving as expected.
